commit_message:
- add support for recursive unmount (#270) - the volume plugin now simply handles attaching/detaching. mounting and unmounting root happens as a part of chroot setup/teardown
- if something goes wrong while setting up the chroot, try to unmount to avoid leaking volumes
- in the busy_mount wrapper around lsof, filter output for the case when it is a bind mount that is busy and processes outside the chroot may have open handles
do some juggling to wrap the unmount call in a retry (#269)
Merge pull request #267 from bmoyles/bmoyles-partition-aware-resize partition-aware resize support

when root volume size support was added, partitioned volumes were not considered. this adds a growpart function for calling growpart against the partition prior to a resize2fs and ensures that fsck, resize2fs, and friends are all called against the partition, not the full block device
Merge pull request #265 from kvick/github_264 Retry for duplicate AMI name fails during register_ami
Github 264 I think the problem was that the retry decorator was expecting kwargs and that wasn't supplied to the decoratee call"
Github issue 264, retry for duplicate name fails with a KeyError
an e2fsck return code of 1 should not be a failure (#262)
fix another spot where we may accidentally try to cat None to int

adjust default root volume size behavior (#261) default should be to not specify a fixed root volume size (but allow for that configuration), and when that volume size is not provided, inherit the size from the base AMI (#261)

cast root vol size to int, fsck before resize (#260) * add -f to fsck to make resize2fs happy

* resize2fs wants fsck before resize. yaml and command line args are being pulled in as strings, need to cast rootvol size to int when retrieving
fix dangling paren typo explosion

allow root volume size (#259) * add convenience properties for directly accessing the context as well as a plugin's configuration

* simple resize2fs command

* allow for (optional) resize2fs before mounting (or if the block device and volume are provided as it would with poolman, resize before we enter the provisioner

* instance-store instances are limited to 10G root volumes, add a guard so we can fail fast should someone request > 10G

* add a root-volume-size argument and root_volume_size default configuration, use that value both in the allocation of the volume as well as in registration

boto.ec2.Volume.delete() simply returns True/False upon success/failure, but spews to ERROR if boto.ec2.Volume.update() is called against a non-existent volume (which ends up dropping an XML error that may confuse end users).
